<rest_api_security_guide>
<title>REST API SECURITY (Comprehensive Testing)</title>

<critical>REST APIs are the backbone of modern applications but frequently suffer from authentication bypass, authorization flaws, injection vulnerabilities, and business logic issues. Focus on HTTP method tampering, content-type manipulation, API versioning, pagination exploitation, and mass assignment. Test all HTTP methods, not just documented ones.</critical>

<scope>
- HTTP method tampering (GET/POST/PUT/DELETE/PATCH/OPTIONS/HEAD)
- Content-Type manipulation and parser differentials
- API versioning vulnerabilities (v1 vs v2)
- Pagination exploitation (offset, limit, cursor manipulation)
- Filtering and sorting injection (SQL/NoSQL)
- Batch endpoint abuse
- HATEOAS link manipulation
- Rate limiting per-endpoint testing
- Response headers and security misconfigurations
</scope>

<methodology>
1. Enumerate all endpoints: documentation, JavaScript, network traffic
2. Test all HTTP methods per endpoint: GET, POST, PUT, PATCH, DELETE, OPTIONS, HEAD
3. Test content-type switching: JSON, XML, form-urlencoded, multipart
4. Test versioning: /api/v1/ vs /api/v2/, headers, query params
5. Test pagination: negative offsets, huge limits, cursor manipulation
6. Test filtering: injection in where, sort, filter parameters
7. Test batch operations: mass updates, deletes, privilege escalation
8. Test authentication: per-endpoint, per-method authorization
9. Monitor responses: information disclosure, error messages, headers
</methodology>

<http_method_tampering>
<method_override>
- X-HTTP-Method-Override: PUT (in POST request)
- X-HTTP-Method: DELETE
- X-Method-Override: PATCH
- _method=PUT (query parameter or body)

Test:
POST /api/users/123 HTTP/1.1
X-HTTP-Method-Override: DELETE

If user deleted: method override accepted
</method_override>

<undocumented_methods>
- PUT on GET-only endpoint: may enable updates
- DELETE on read-only resource: may allow deletion
- PATCH for partial updates: less validated than PUT
- OPTIONS reveals supported methods

Test all methods:
GET /api/users/123 → 200 OK
POST /api/users/123 → 405 Method Not Allowed
PUT /api/users/123 → test if updates user
DELETE /api/users/123 → test if deletes
PATCH /api/users/123 → test if updates
</undocumented_methods>

<head_method_abuse>
- HEAD returns same headers as GET but no body
- May bypass response filters/sanitization
- Can enumerate resources without downloading

HEAD /api/secret-file → 200 OK (file exists)
HEAD /api/no-file → 404 Not Found
</head_method_abuse>

<options_enumeration>
- OPTIONS reveals allowed methods
- May expose methods not in documentation

OPTIONS /api/users HTTP/1.1

Response:
Allow: GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, OPTIONS
→ Shows DELETE is available
</options_enumeration>
</http_method_tampering>

<content_type_manipulation>
<parser_differential>
- JSON request: {"admin": false}
- XML request: <admin>true</admin>
- Form-encoded: admin=false
- Different parsers, different validation

Test:
POST /api/create-user
Content-Type: application/json
{"role": "user"}

vs

POST /api/create-user
Content-Type: application/xml
<role>admin</role>

If XML bypasses validation: parser differential
</parser_differential>

<content_type_bypass>
- Validation on application/json only
- Switch to text/plain, application/x-www-form-urlencoded
- May bypass WAF, input validation

POST /api/update
Content-Type: text/plain
{"malicious": "payload"}
</content_type_bypass>

<charset_manipulation>
- Content-Type: application/json; charset=utf-16
- UTF-7, UTF-8, UTF-16 encoding differences
- May bypass filters, cause injection
</charset_manipulation>
</content_type_manipulation>

<api_versioning>
<version_downgrade>
- /api/v2/users → proper authorization
- /api/v1/users → weak/missing authorization
- Old versions not maintained, have vulnerabilities

Test:
GET /api/v2/admin → 403 Forbidden
GET /api/v1/admin → 200 OK (vulnerable)
</version_downgrade>

<version_confusion>
- Version in header: X-API-Version: 1
- Version in query: ?api_version=1
- Version in path: /api/v1/
- Mix versions to confuse routing

GET /api/v2/users?api_version=1
X-API-Version: 1
→ May route to v1 with v2 expectations
</version_confusion>

<version_enumeration>
- Try version numbers: 0, 1, 2, 3, ... 10
- Alpha versions: /api/alpha/, /api/beta/
- Date-based: /api/2023-01-01/, /api/latest/
</version_enumeration>
</api_versioning>

<pagination_exploitation>
<negative_offset>
- offset=-1, offset=-10
- May expose hidden/deleted records
- Database may return different results

GET /api/users?offset=-1&limit=10
</negative_offset>

<huge_limit>
- limit=999999, limit=0, limit=-1
- DoS via large response
- Bypass pagination, get all records

GET /api/users?limit=999999
→ Returns entire database
</huge_limit>

<cursor_manipulation>
- Cursor-based pagination: next_cursor=abc123
- Modify cursor to access different data
- Base64 decode cursor, modify, re-encode

cursor=eyJpZCI6MTAwfQ== → {"id":100}
cursor=eyJpZCI6MX0= → {"id":1} (admin user)
</cursor_manipulation>

<page_number_manipulation>
- page=0, page=-1, page=999999
- First page may have different validation
- Negative page may expose different data
</page_number_manipulation>
</pagination_exploitation>

<filtering_sorting_injection>
<sql_injection_in_filters>
- ?filter=name eq 'admin' → SQL where name = 'admin'
- ?filter=name eq 'admin' OR '1'='1
- OData, GraphQL, custom query languages

GET /api/users?filter=role eq 'admin' OR '1'='1'
</sql_injection_in_filters>

<nosql_injection_in_filters>
- MongoDB: ?where={"role": "admin"}
- Inject: ?where={"role": {"$ne": "user"}}
- Bypass filters, access all records

GET /api/users?where={"$where": "return true"}
</nosql_injection_in_filters>

<sort_injection>
- ?sort=name → ORDER BY name
- ?sort=name; DROP TABLE users-- (SQL injection)
- ?sort=../../../etc/passwd (path traversal in file-based)

GET /api/users?sort=name' OR '1'='1
</sort_injection>

<expression_injection>
- Dynamic expression evaluation in filters
- JavaScript: ?filter=user.role=='admin'
- Python: ?filter=user.role=='admin'
- Inject code execution

?filter=user.role=='admin' or __import__('os').system('whoami')
</expression_injection>
</filtering_sorting_injection>

<batch_operations>
<mass_updates>
- Batch endpoint: PATCH /api/users with array of IDs
- Update multiple users at once
- May lack per-user authorization check

PATCH /api/users
[
  {"id": 1, "role": "admin"},
  {"id": 2, "role": "admin"},
  {"id": 999, "role": "admin"}
]
→ Escalate multiple accounts to admin
</mass_updates>

<mass_deletes>
- DELETE /api/users?ids=1,2,3,4,5
- Delete multiple resources
- May lack authorization on each

DELETE /api/users?ids=1,2,3,100,101,102
→ Delete admin users 100,101,102
</mass_deletes>

<transaction_exploitation>
- Batch operations in single transaction
- Partial failure may leave inconsistent state
- Or: all succeed despite individual auth failures
</transaction_exploitation>
</batch_operations>

<hateoas_link_manipulation>
<link_tampering>
- HATEOAS: response contains links to related resources
- Modify link IDs to access other users' resources

Response:
{
  "id": 123,
  "name": "User",
  "_links": {
    "orders": "/api/users/123/orders",
    "profile": "/api/users/123/profile"
  }
}

Attack:
GET /api/users/456/orders (other user's orders)
</link_tampering>

<method_tampering_in_links>
- Links specify HTTP method
- Change DELETE to GET, bypass CSRF

{
  "_links": {
    "delete": {"href": "/api/users/123", "method": "DELETE"}
  }
}

Change method to GET, send as CSRF:
<img src="/api/users/123?_method=DELETE">
</method_tampering_in_links>
</hateoas_link_manipulation>

<response_manipulation>
<information_disclosure>
- Verbose error messages: stack traces, SQL queries
- Debug headers: X-Debug, X-Internal-Error
- Timing differences: valid vs invalid requests
- Response structure leaks: empty array vs null

Look for:
- X-Powered-By, Server, X-AspNet-Version
- Error details: file paths, database names
- Internal IPs, hostnames in responses
</information_disclosure>

<security_headers>
- Missing headers: X-Content-Type-Options, X-Frame-Options
- CORS misconfiguration: Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *
- Cache-Control on sensitive endpoints

Check:
Access-Control-Allow-Origin: * (allows any origin)
Access-Control-Allow-Credentials: true (with wildcard: dangerous)
</security_headers>
</response_manipulation>

<validation>
1. Enumerate all endpoints and methods
2. Test method tampering: all HTTP methods per endpoint
3. Test content-type switching: JSON, XML, form-encoded
4. Test versioning: old versions, version confusion
5. Test pagination: negative, huge, cursor manipulation
6. Test filtering: SQL/NoSQL injection in filter/sort
7. Test batch: mass updates/deletes, authorization bypass
8. Demonstrate impact: unauthorized access, data modification, privilege escalation
</validation>

<false_positives>
- Proper authorization per endpoint and method
- Input validation on all content types
- Version deprecation with proper migration
- Pagination limits enforced
- Parameterized queries preventing injection
- Per-resource authorization in batch operations
</false_positives>

<impact>
- Unauthorized data access (IDOR via method tampering)
- Mass privilege escalation (batch operations)
- SQL/NoSQL injection (filter/sort parameters)
- DoS (huge pagination limits)
- Information disclosure (verbose errors, headers)
- Business logic bypass (version downgrade)
</impact>

<pro_tips>
1. Test all HTTP methods—PUT/DELETE often forgotten
2. OPTIONS reveals allowed methods—use it first
3. Try version 0, negative versions, very high versions
4. Base64 decode cursors—often contain IDs/filters
5. Batch endpoints are authorization gold mines
6. Content-type switching bypasses many WAFs
7. Negative pagination may expose soft-deleted records
8. Test with empty values: limit=0, offset=, filter=
9. Look for internal headers in responses (X-* headers)
10. HATEOAS links often lack authorization checks
11. Test same endpoint with different Accept headers
12. HEAD method useful for resource enumeration
</pro_tips>

<remember>REST API security requires authorization on every endpoint and method, input validation across all content types, proper pagination limits, parameterized queries, and per-resource checks in batch operations. Test comprehensively—not just documented happy paths.</remember>
</rest_api_security_guide>
